Content-Type: text/enriched
Text-Width: 70

Episode 1


Commands learned
	 C-s (isearch-forward) - sets a mark matching the input and looks for all matches from 
	 the mark down to the end of the <x-bg-color><param>pink</param><x-color><param>black</param>cursor</x-color></x-bg-color>. Move the <x-bg-color><param>pink</param><x-color><param>black</param>cursor</x-color></x-bg-color> to set the region.
	 C-x r t string-rectangle - With marked region, type in replacement.


Example text
	var 1
	var 2
	var 3
End example text


Instructions
1. Set cursor to beginning of var 1
2. C-s
3. <x-bg-color><param>yellow1</param><x-color><param>black</param>var</x-color></x-bg-color>
4. move cursor down to after <x-bg-color><param>yellow1</param><x-color><param>black</param>var</x-color></x-bg-color> 3
5. C-x r t
6. this.


Replaces <x-bg-color><param>yellow1</param><x-color><param>black</param>var</x-color></x-bg-color> with this. in rectangle that was marked.
Opposite of C-s (search forward), is C-r (search backwards). Same idea.


______________________________________________________________________________________________________


Episode 2


Commands learned
	 F3 (kmacro-start-macro) - macro that remembers every keystroke
	 F4 activate macro
	 C-u # - # is some number for repeating any command after this command # of times	 

	 


one	1
two	2
three	3
four	4
five	5
six	6
seven	7
eight	8
nine	9
ten	10



DEFINE A MACRO WITH F3


1. start at beginning of line (at one)
2. F3 (start macro)
3. A-e (bring to end of paragraph)
4. C-A 
5. C-k (kill line and put in memory)
6. BCS
7. C-u 9 C-p (repeat previous line nine times)
8. C-e
9. tab
10. C-y (yank number)
11. F4 (end macro)
12. C-u 9 F4 (repeat macro nine times)


